   {:e #blake3 "3d221da4adb1e33b4dc55c4f56c796d73a883551ebe07be4edec4c35f414c465" :a :harvest/accomplishments :v "Session entity: :recon/trace-ef31b45439927b35; Session entity: :recon/trace-9397d7396b72907e; SESSION-031 DOG-FOOD: DEEP REFLECTION ON USING BRAID AS AN AGENT. I am paying close attention to every moment of flow and friction as I use this system. Here is my honest, detailed analysis:\n\nWHAT FLOWS WELL:\n1. SEED ORIENTATION (A+): The seed assembled 73 state entries, constraints, and warnings in one command. I immediately knew: 330 open tasks, 280 ready, F(S)=0.67, 14 stale files. Zero re-orientation needed. This is the harvest/seed promise delivered.\n\n2. CRYSTALLIZATION FEEDBACK IS MAGICAL: When I ran braid observe with my session start notes, the Δ-cryst feedback triggered immediately — it showed me related knowledge and confirmed my observation was anchored to spec. This FEELS like the system understanding what I'm saying, not just storing it. The hippocampal pattern completion metaphor is experientially accurate.\n\n3. P(t) METRIC IS THE RIGHT COMPLEMENT TO F(S): Seeing P(t)=0.60 tells me 'you have closed 60% of all tasks.' F(S)=0.67 tells me 'formal verification depth is moderate.' Both are useful, neither alone is sufficient. The dual-metric dashboard works.\n\n4. CRB-PREVIEW WOULD HAVE CAUGHT NAME COLLISION: My search for META- tasks returned 22 results including OLD META-1/META-2/META-3 tasks from Session 024 alongside the NEW metabolic META-1/META-2/META-3. The naming collision is confusing — the old and new tasks share prefixes. CRB-PREVIEW would flag this at creation time.\n\nWHAT CREATES FRICTION:\n1. TASK SEARCH BY PREFIX IS AMBIGUOUS: 'braid task search META-' returns 22 results mixing old workstream META tasks with new Metabolic Store META tasks. Need better namespacing or filtering. The short_title helps but doesn't solve the collision.\n\n2. STATUS COMMAND IS SLOW: braid status takes ~5 seconds to complete (bilateral analysis, fitness computation, trace staleness check, methodology gaps). During rapid task execution, I want a fast 'am I on track?' signal, not a full diagnostic. A 'braid status --fast' that skips bilateral/trace would be useful.\n\n3. HARVEST WARNING STILL FIRED BRIEFLY: After recording the observation + checking status + searching tasks, the harvest warning appeared. But this is CORRECT behavior now — I made a novel observation (delta-cryst non-zero), so the urgency signal is genuine. The metabolic urgency is working. The friction is that I need to decide whether to harvest now or continue working. Previously this was annoying (false alarm). Now it is informative (real signal). This is a QUALITATIVE improvement.\n\n4. THE STORE IS GETTING LARGE: 33,152 datoms. Each braid command loads the entire store from disk. At ~33k datoms, load time is <100ms which is fine. But the trajectory is ~800 datoms/session. At 100 sessions, that is 80k datoms. At 200 sessions, 160k datoms. The .cache/ system helps but we should monitor.\n\n5. R(t) ROUTING FEELS STALE: ST-3 has been the top recommendation for 3 sessions. The routing weights are in 'defaults' mode (no learning yet — need 50 outcomes). But the metabolic system should provide continuous outcome signals (META-8). Until META-8 is implemented, R(t) will remain in default mode.\n\nWHAT DELIGHTS:\n1. The OBSERVE COMMAND with crystallization feedback creates a genuine dialogue. I say something, the store tells me what it means in context. This is not just logging — it is CONVERSATION with accumulated knowledge.\n\n2. P(t) INCREASING ACROSS SESSIONS is visible and motivating: Session 029 = 0.55, Session 030 = 0.60. The project is making real progress.\n\n3. The METABOLIC DELTA is already providing useful signal even before META-7 (session dashboard) is implemented. When I observe something, I know immediately whether it is anchored to spec.\n\nOVERALL ASSESSMENT CHANGE FROM SESSION 030:\nSession 030 grade: B+ (strong core abstractions, weak operational ergonomics)\nSession 031 early assessment: A- (metabolic system addresses the ergonomics gap)\n\nThe system has crossed an inflection point. It went from 'database that stores what I tell it' to 'knowledge system that tells me what my observations mean.' The crystallization feedback loop is the single biggest UX improvement in the project history. TRACES TO: INV-GUIDANCE-014, INV-BILATERAL-001, INV-STORE-014, INV-SEED-001.; Session entity: :recon/trace-f0ce6a1869b4091f; Session entity: :recon/trace-6807ae44cc96991f; SESSION-031 DOG-FOOD START: Observations on system UX as I begin a new session. (1) SEED WORKED PERFECTLY — I ran braid seed with my task description, got immediate orientation with 73 state entries, 4 warnings, and constraints. The bilateral divergence warning (Phi=313.8) is concerning but I know from Session 030 that it's structural (179 cycles in the spec graph). (2) STATUS SHOWS P(t)=0.60 — The metric I added last session is immediately useful. I can see progress. But F(S) dropped back to 0.67 from 0.68 — likely because the new metabolic schema attribute changed the denominator. (3) R(t) STILL RECOMMENDS ST-3 — The session trajectory ring buffer has been the top recommendation for 2 sessions. This suggests R(t) weights are sticky or the impact formula overweights this specific task. (4) THE METABOLIC SYSTEM IS LIVE BUT INVISIBLE — delta-crystallization is being computed on every transaction now, but I can't SEE the cumulative delta anywhere in status. META-7 (session dashboard) would fix this. (5) 330 open tasks feel like a lot — but 280 are ready, meaning 50 are blocked. The blocked count grew from 43 to 50, which means some of the new metabolic tasks added dependencies that blocked previously-ready tasks. This is expected. TRACES TO: INV-BILATERAL-001, INV-INTERFACE-008.; Session entity: :recon/trace-0926b5e14a6f3621; Session entity: :recon/trace-e24b3bbb195efd49" :op :assert}
